Dialogue: 0,0:00:00.06,0:00:02.86,Default,,0,0,0,,In 1982, the fruits of a partnership between
Dialogue: 0,0:00:02.86,0:00:05.92,Default,,0,0,0,,Sony and Philips were released to the music-loving public,
Dialogue: 0,0:00:05.92,0:00:11.25,Default,,0,0,0,,The Compact Disc, or CD, was unveiled as the first consumer digital audio format.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:11.25,0:00:16.48,Default,,0,0,0,,These 12 cm discs could store up to 74 minutes of perfect quality digital audio,
Dialogue: 0,0:00:16.48,0:00:20.76,Default,,0,0,0,,and as was famously demonstrated many times over, were immune from liquid damage,
Dialogue: 0,0:00:20.76,0:00:24.59,Default,,0,0,0,,could withstand significant scratching, and could be played without wearing them down
Dialogue: 0,0:00:24.59,0:00:27.07,Default,,0,0,0,,for a theoretically infinite number of times.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:27.07,0:00:30.21,Default,,0,0,0,,That’s because, unlike all previous sound formats where
Dialogue: 0,0:00:30.21,0:00:35.82,Default,,0,0,0,,sound is encoded as an analog impression of the sound wave on plastic discs or magnetic tape,
Dialogue: 0,0:00:35.82,0:00:38.78,Default,,0,0,0,,the sound on a CD is encoded as a series of samples,
Dialogue: 0,0:00:38.78,0:00:42.45,Default,,0,0,0,,which function as a set of instructions on how to recreate the sound.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:42.45,0:00:46.99,Default,,0,0,0,,The Compact Disc was a BIG FREAKING DEAL in many ways!
Dialogue: 0,0:00:46.99,0:00:50.30,Default,,0,0,0,,It represented a giant leap in convenience for the consumer,
Dialogue: 0,0:00:50.30,0:00:54.52,Default,,0,0,0,,quality of the recorded sound, and in raw data storage capacity.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:54.52,0:00:58.64,Default,,0,0,0,,That last bit wouldn’t be too relevant to the computing industry for some time,
Dialogue: 0,0:00:58.82,0:01:01.47,Default,,0,0,0,,but it solved the central problem of digital sound--
Dialogue: 0,0:01:01.47,0:01:05.71,Default,,0,0,0,,needing a, for the time, absurdly massive amount of raw data,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:05.71,0:01:08.81,Default,,0,0,0,,Before we get too far into the specifics of the Compact Disc,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:08.81,0:01:12.75,Default,,0,0,0,,it’s time to dig a little deeper into how digital sound actually works.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:12.75,0:01:15.84,Default,,0,0,0,,Recall from my last video that an analog-to-digital converter
Dialogue: 0,0:01:15.84,0:01:20.54,Default,,0,0,0,,is taking instantaneous samples of the analog signal at a specific sampling frequency,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:20.54,0:01:26.80,Default,,0,0,0,,Then, a DAC can recreate the original analog signal with only those samples.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:26.80,0:01:30.25,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, a lot of people think that this can’t possibly work to recreate
Dialogue: 0,0:01:30.25,0:01:33.16,Default,,0,0,0,,all the detail in the original analog sound wave.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:33.16,0:01:37.04,Default,,0,0,0,,But thanks to mathematics, we know that it can, and does.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:37.04,0:01:40.43,Default,,0,0,0,,It’s time to explore the Nyquist-Shannon sampling theorem.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:40.43,0:01:44.49,Default,,0,0,0,,This theorem was co-discovered by E.T.Whittaker and Vladimir Kotelnikov.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:44.49,0:01:50.28,Default,,0,0,0,,So it is also, but less commonly, referred to as the...
Dialogue: 0,0:01:50.28,0:01:53.80,Default,,0,0,0,,Anyway, Harry Nyquist and Claude Shannon, along with the other two,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:53.80,0:01:58.09,Default,,0,0,0,,discovered that a band-limited signal, that means a signal which does not contain
Dialogue: 0,0:01:58.09,0:02:03.24,Default,,0,0,0,,frequency above a certain limit, can be perfectly described and perfectly reconstructed
Dialogue: 0,0:02:03.24,0:02:07.32,Default,,0,0,0,,by taking instantaneous samples at twice the rate of the frequency limit,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:07.32,0:02:11.64,Default,,0,0,0,,This gets a little complicated, so I’m going to explain it as best as I can,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:11.64,0:02:17.56,Default,,0,0,0,,Our hearing itself is bandlimited. Though frequencies exist in nature above 20,000 hertz,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:17.56,0:02:23.41,Default,,0,0,0,,our ears cannot detect anything above that frequency. Some people claim they can but,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:23.41,0:02:26.99,Default,,0,0,0,,well, most people rapidly lose their hearing at those high frequencies as they age,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:26.99,0:02:31.00,Default,,0,0,0,,and I’m talking like as they leave childhood, so let’s just not go there.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:31.00,0:02:34.86,Default,,0,0,0,,With the knowledge that anything above 20,000 hertz will just not be audible,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:34.86,0:02:37.85,Default,,0,0,0,,we can therefore capture all of the audio we can hear
Dialogue: 0,0:02:37.85,0:02:41.06,Default,,0,0,0,,by only recording sounds below 20 kilohertz.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:41.06,0:02:44.48,Default,,0,0,0,,Passing an analog input through what’s called a low-pass filter
Dialogue: 0,0:02:44.48,0:02:48.01,Default,,0,0,0,,will eliminate any frequencies above a specified point.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:48.01,0:02:51.02,Default,,0,0,0,,There’s no sense in recording sounds we can’t hear, so we can use
Dialogue: 0,0:02:51.02,0:02:54.56,Default,,0,0,0,,a low-pass filter to eliminate frequency components above 20 kilohertz.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:54.56,0:02:57.74,Default,,0,0,0,,And we end up with a signal that represents all that we can hear.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:57.74,0:03:00.67,Default,,0,0,0,,And is, importantly, band-limited.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:00.67,0:03:03.00,Default,,0,0,0,,For now, we’re going to assume this can work perfectly,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:03.00,0:03:08.08,Default,,0,0,0,,so we’ll say that any signals above 20 kHz cannot pass through the low pass filter.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:08.08,0:03:11.76,Default,,0,0,0,,Nyquist-Shannon tells us that by sampling at a rate of 40 kilohertz,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:11.76,0:03:15.96,Default,,0,0,0,,we can capture all the detail possible in this newly band-limited signal.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:15.96,0:03:20.00,Default,,0,0,0,,That may sound a little unintuitive, but let’s explain why it’s true.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:20.00,0:03:23.88,Default,,0,0,0,,When you have a band-limited signal, certain types of sounds get reduced
Dialogue: 0,0:03:23.88,0:03:28.19,Default,,0,0,0,,to a representation of themselves made as a sum of sine wave harmonics.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:28.19,0:03:31.61,Default,,0,0,0,,Fourier transformation, which is another complicated math subject
Dialogue: 0,0:03:31.61,0:03:34.08,Default,,0,0,0,,that will rear its ugly head a little later, means that we can
Dialogue: 0,0:03:34.08,0:03:37.86,Default,,0,0,0,,represent any waveform as a sum of sine wave harmonics.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:37.86,0:03:40.39,Default,,0,0,0,,The most classic illustration of this is a square wave.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:40.39,0:03:44.51,Default,,0,0,0,,A true square wave looks like this, but to actually reproduce this signal
Dialogue: 0,0:03:44.51,0:03:48.85,Default,,0,0,0,,would require near infinite bandwidth. And I know what you’re saying, that seems silly.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:48.85,0:03:51.37,Default,,0,0,0,,This is just a rapid hard cut in and out of a signal.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:51.74,0:03:55.02,Default,,0,0,0,,Like flipping a light switch on and off, Ehh, that’s true.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:55.02,0:03:58.23,Default,,0,0,0,,But if we could produce this signal, then this vertical piece,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:58.23,0:04:01.12,Default,,0,0,0,,which represents an instantaneous increase in amplitude,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:01.12,0:04:04.52,Default,,0,0,0,,would require a frequency response that’s ridiculously high.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:04.52,0:04:08.47,Default,,0,0,0,,See if we can make that instantaneous shift from low to high intensity,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:08.47,0:04:12.37,Default,,0,0,0,,then we must be able to produce the same shift downward in the same amount of time,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:12.37,0:04:16.25,Default,,0,0,0,,which is no time at all if it truly is instantaneous.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:16.25,0:04:21.39,Default,,0,0,0,,To do that would require infinite bandwidth, that’s more than we have to play with.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:21.39,0:04:27.20,Default,,0,0,0,,So when this signal is passed through a low-pass filter of 20 kilohertz, it comes out like this.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:27.20,0:04:32.52,Default,,0,0,0,,This is the sum of harmonics that would create this square wave via a fourier transform,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:32.52,0:04:36.42,Default,,0,0,0,,but the highest frequency harmonic possible is 20 kilohertz.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:36.42,0:04:38.83,Default,,0,0,0,,Because we’ve placed a bandlimit on the input,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:38.83,0:04:42.57,Default,,0,0,0,,we’re dealing with nothing but sine waves now, piled on top of each other.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:42.57,0:04:46.40,Default,,0,0,0,,We are constructing any other waveforms as a sum of sine wave harmonics,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:46.40,0:04:50.48,Default,,0,0,0,,and this explains why the Nyquist-Shannon theorem holds true.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:50.48,0:04:54.81,Default,,0,0,0,,If the sample goes from the lowest possible to the highest possible value and back,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:54.81,0:04:58.06,Default,,0,0,0,,the only waveform that can hit those three samples is
Dialogue: 0,0:04:58.06,0:05:01.77,Default,,0,0,0,,a sine wave at the Nyquist frequency of 20 kilohertz.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:01.77,0:05:06.39,Default,,0,0,0,,We can’t describe any frequencies higher than 20 kilohertz,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:06.39,0:05:09.82,Default,,0,0,0,,but just two samples per cycle is enough to define our highest possible frequency.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:09.82,0:05:13.68,Default,,0,0,0,,When you band-limit a signal, you eliminate all of the high frequency harmonics
Dialogue: 0,0:05:13.68,0:05:16.51,Default,,0,0,0,,that could define a square wave with greater detail than this.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:17.05,0:05:21.20,Default,,0,0,0,,Now before you cry foul that this is creating detail where there shouldn’t be detail,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:21.20,0:05:26.51,Default,,0,0,0,,just remember that your hearing is just as bandlimited as the output of the low-pass filter.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:26.51,0:05:30.00,Default,,0,0,0,,And also keep in mind that the whole chain here is messy.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:30.38,0:05:34.01,Default,,0,0,0,,Everything in nature will oscillate with a sudden impulse of energy.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:34.01,0:05:37.08,Default,,0,0,0,,Even if a true square wave were to burst on the scene,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:37.08,0:05:40.22,Default,,0,0,0,,your eardrums will oscillate between the peaks in energy,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:40.22,0:05:43.46,Default,,0,0,0,,sort of like the wiggly wobblies in this bandlimited waveform.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:43.46,0:05:45.84,Default,,0,0,0,,So they key here is, don’t worry about it!
Dialogue: 0,0:05:45.84,0:05:51.26,Default,,0,0,0,,This drove me crazy for days but the fact is, this is just how sound waves and nature work.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:51.68,0:05:54.59,Default,,0,0,0,,Any signal can be represented as a sum of sine waves,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:54.59,0:05:58.62,Default,,0,0,0,,and bandlimiting it simply forces these oscillations into existence.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:58.62,0:06:01.69,Default,,0,0,0,,The most pressing issue with this representation is that
Dialogue: 0,0:06:01.69,0:06:05.13,Default,,0,0,0,,it can create ringing artifacts as a result of the Gibb’s phenomenon.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:05.13,0:06:07.52,Default,,0,0,0,,But now we’re getting into really nitpicky stuff,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:07.52,0:06:11.13,Default,,0,0,0,,and you could easily argue that this would happen even in analog systems
Dialogue: 0,0:06:11.13,0:06:14.70,Default,,0,0,0,,due once again, to natural oscillations. Either in the physical realm,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:14.70,0:06:18.75,Default,,0,0,0,,such as the fact that both a phonograph needle and loudspeaker driver have mass
Dialogue: 0,0:06:18.75,0:06:21.18,Default,,0,0,0,,and thus cannot move instantaneously,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:21.18,0:06:23.53,Default,,0,0,0,,So they will oscillate at their own harmonic frequency
Dialogue: 0,0:06:23.53,0:06:25.58,Default,,0,0,0,,and create their own ringing artifacts anyway.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:25.58,0:06:30.99,Default,,0,0,0,,And also the electrical realm because the nature of any circuit will have some oscillations, too.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:30.99,0:06:32.75,Default,,0,0,0,,So again, don’t worry about it.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:32.75,0:06:36.44,Default,,0,0,0,,Now comes the part that sounds crazy but is completely true,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:36.44,0:06:38.46,Default,,0,0,0,,and I can show it to you in a moment.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:38.46,0:06:42.88,Default,,0,0,0,,Nyquist-shannon tells us that if we simply have twice the number of samples per second
Dialogue: 0,0:06:42.88,0:06:44.83,Default,,0,0,0,,as the frequency of our signal’s band limit,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:44.83,0:06:48.54,Default,,0,0,0,,the exact bandlimited signal can be reproduced perfectly.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:48.54,0:06:52.62,Default,,0,0,0,,And I mean, literally perfectly, using only those samples.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:52.62,0:06:55.60,Default,,0,0,0,,This is admittedly weird, so let’s talk through it.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:55.60,0:07:00.01,Default,,0,0,0,,Imagine an ADC is recording a sound. Every 40 thousandth of a second
Dialogue: 0,0:07:00.01,0:07:02.99,Default,,0,0,0,,it takes an instantaneous reading of the signal it receives.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:02.99,0:07:05.68,Default,,0,0,0,,By quantifying it on a digital scale of our choosing,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:05.68,0:07:08.79,Default,,0,0,0,,it creates 40 thousand discrete samples every second.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:08.79,0:07:14.02,Default,,0,0,0,,But remember, that signal has passed through a low-pass filter before it reached the ADC,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:14.02,0:07:17.74,Default,,0,0,0,,so it does not contain any frequencies above 20 kilohertz.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:17.74,0:07:21.13,Default,,0,0,0,,The truly mind-blowing part about Nyquist-Shannon is that
Dialogue: 0,0:07:21.13,0:07:26.55,Default,,0,0,0,,the samples we get from this bandlimited signal can ONLY reproduce the original signal.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:26.55,0:07:29.92,Default,,0,0,0,,There is only ONE signal that can possibly produce
Dialogue: 0,0:07:29.92,0:07:32.80,Default,,0,0,0,,the exact series of samples that the ADC recorded.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:33.41,0:07:36.01,Default,,0,0,0,,Again, this is because we are dealing with a bandlimit.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:36.01,0:07:40.65,Default,,0,0,0,,Without a bandlimit in place, the samples could be defining parts of other strange waveforms
Dialogue: 0,0:07:40.65,0:07:43.32,Default,,0,0,0,,due to aliasing, but when adhering to this bandlimit,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:43.32,0:07:47.64,Default,,0,0,0,,the resulting string of samples can only define exactly one waveform,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:47.64,0:07:51.20,Default,,0,0,0,,There is literally only one mathematical solution for the bandlimited waveform
Dialogue: 0,0:07:51.20,0:07:53.26,Default,,0,0,0,,that would pass through all samples.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:53.26,0:07:54.54,Default,,0,0,0,,(Mind blow)
Dialogue: 0,0:07:54.56,0:07:56.97,Default,,0,0,0,,This is some complicated stuff here, But just know that
Dialogue: 0,0:07:56.97,0:08:01.25,Default,,0,0,0,,if I have any series of samples, and I assume these are representing a bandlimited signal,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:01.25,0:08:04.28,Default,,0,0,0,,then they can only possibly satisfy one waveform.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:04.28,0:08:07.50,Default,,0,0,0,,And that, ladies and gentlemen, is why the myth that digital sound
Dialogue: 0,0:08:07.50,0:08:10.75,Default,,0,0,0,,creates a stair step pattern in the output is false.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:10.75,0:08:14.00,Default,,0,0,0,,But the weirder bit is that the DAC very well might.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:14.00,0:08:15.88,Default,,0,0,0,,But before you freak out, that doesn’t mean
Dialogue: 0,0:08:15.88,0:08:19.68,Default,,0,0,0,,any stair-steppy signal has ever come out of a DAC or CD player or anything,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:19.68,0:08:24.72,Default,,0,0,0,,And that’s because of the same low-pass filter that originally bandlimited the input signal,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:24.72,0:08:29.26,Default,,0,0,0,,Many digital to analog converters are actually quite simple. They use a resistor ladder,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:29.26,0:08:33.96,Default,,0,0,0,,which is tied to the actual bits in each discrete sample, to produce the appropriate voltage.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:33.96,0:08:35.96,Default,,0,0,0,,I don’t want to go on too much of a tangent here,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:35.96,0:08:38.63,Default,,0,0,0,,but they are really neat and explain how the simplest DACs work.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:39.17,0:08:41.71,Default,,0,0,0,,Each bit of the sample is tied to a resistor.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:41.71,0:08:44.90,Default,,0,0,0,,If it’s a one, the resistor is activated and passes voltage through it.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:44.90,0:08:46.78,Default,,0,0,0,,And if it’s a zero, the resistor is not.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:46.78,0:08:49.43,Default,,0,0,0,,The network of resistors will create a unique voltage for
Dialogue: 0,0:08:49.43,0:08:51.56,Default,,0,0,0,,each possible combination of bits, and thus
Dialogue: 0,0:08:51.56,0:08:55.62,Default,,0,0,0,,you now end up with zeros and ones equalling a voltage of however specific you want.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:56.25,0:08:59.84,Default,,0,0,0,,A 16 bit DAC, like those used in the Compact Disc standard
Dialogue: 0,0:08:59.84,0:09:01.70,Default,,0,0,0,,(most of the time--we’ll get to that)
Dialogue: 0,0:09:01.70,0:09:05.71,Default,,0,0,0,,will have 16 resistors, each controlled by one bit of the datastream.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:05.71,0:09:10.22,Default,,0,0,0,,These feed into intermediary resistors to create all of the possible voltages,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:10.22,0:09:13.53,Default,,0,0,0,,But the more bits you add, the more accurate these resistors have to become,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:13.53,0:09:16.84,Default,,0,0,0,,which helps explain why the earliest DACs were very expensive.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:16.84,0:09:19.67,Default,,0,0,0,,The technology to produce resistors in an integrated circuit
Dialogue: 0,0:09:19.67,0:09:26.45,Default,,0,0,0,,within an accuracy within approximately .000015%, was expensive for a while,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:26.45,0:09:29.25,Default,,0,0,0,,Anyway, these R-2R DACs, as they’re sometimes called,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:29.25,0:09:32.56,Default,,0,0,0,,will produce a stair-step waveform from the output of the resistor ladder.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:32.99,0:09:34.87,Default,,0,0,0,,This is what’s called sample-and-hold.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:34.87,0:09:39.17,Default,,0,0,0,,Each sample sustains the given voltage level until the next sample is received by the DAC.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:39.76,0:09:44.34,Default,,0,0,0,,This had led to many, many, far too many people believing that this is the signal that
Dialogue: 0,0:09:44.34,0:09:47.00,Default,,0,0,0,,comes out of your CD player and goes into your amplifier.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:47.00,0:09:50.61,Default,,0,0,0,,It is easy to imagine this blocky-looking waveform screwing around
Dialogue: 0,0:09:50.61,0:09:52.78,Default,,0,0,0,,with your favorite recording of Beethoven’s 9th.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:52.78,0:09:55.90,Default,,0,0,0,,But you forget, dear audiophile, that the stair-steppy waveform
Dialogue: 0,0:09:55.90,0:09:58.74,Default,,0,0,0,,will pass through a low-pass filter on its way out.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:59.04,0:10:02.78,Default,,0,0,0,,And that filter will create the same bandlimit on the output from the DAC,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:02.78,0:10:05.47,Default,,0,0,0,,as was placed on the input of the ADC.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:06.07,0:10:11.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, what this means, is that the output from the DAC is also bandlimited to 20 kilohertz.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:11.00,0:10:15.16,Default,,0,0,0,,And why does that matter? Because the very stair-steppy nature of the resistor ladder’s
Dialogue: 0,0:10:15.16,0:10:18.43,Default,,0,0,0,,output is impossible with a bandlimit of 20 kilohertz.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:18.84,0:10:23.16,Default,,0,0,0,,Just like our square wave example, these vertical components require infinite bandwidth.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:23.74,0:10:24.89,Default,,0,0,0,,Good luck with that.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:25.30,0:10:28.76,Default,,0,0,0,,But what’s even weirder, and kinda difficult to grasp, is that
Dialogue: 0,0:10:28.76,0:10:32.70,Default,,0,0,0,,because the output of the DAC has the same bandlimit as the ADC did,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:32.70,0:10:35.07,Default,,0,0,0,,now we are dealing with Nyquist-Shannon again.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:35.53,0:10:40.23,Default,,0,0,0,,And the truly strange-but-true part of this, is that the only possible result of the output
Dialogue: 0,0:10:40.23,0:10:44.10,Default,,0,0,0,,from the low pass filter is the original waveform that the ADC recorded.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:44.72,0:10:46.52,Default,,0,0,0,,Remember, with a bandlimited signal,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:46.52,0:10:49.92,Default,,0,0,0,,we can represent all of the detail within that signal with discrete samples,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:49.92,0:10:53.00,Default,,0,0,0,,and with only a sample rate that is twice the bandlimit frequency.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:53.59,0:10:56.80,Default,,0,0,0,,If we create a waveform that passes through all of the samples,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:56.80,0:11:00.86,Default,,0,0,0,,then it must be the original waveform recorded by the ADC.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:00.97,0:11:04.67,Default,,0,0,0,,The fact that the waveform comes out of the resistor ladder all choppy-like doesn’t
Dialogue: 0,0:11:04.67,0:11:08.68,Default,,0,0,0,,matter in the slightest, because the low pass filter will bandlimit it and get rid of the
Dialogue: 0,0:11:08.68,0:11:13.32,Default,,0,0,0,,choppies, Now it can only contain frequencies of 20 kilohertz or below.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:13.71,0:11:17.93,Default,,0,0,0,,Remember, the vertical parts of the stair-step pattern are impossible with that bandlimit,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:17.93,0:11:19.16,Default,,0,0,0,,so they just get smoothed out.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:19.73,0:11:24.26,Default,,0,0,0,,And since we know that the DAC was outputting the correct voltage level with each sample,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:24.26,0:11:26.71,Default,,0,0,0,,all of the samples must have been satisfied.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:26.71,0:11:30.04,Default,,0,0,0,,Which means that after the LPF smooths the waveform,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:30.04,0:11:32.50,Default,,0,0,0,,it must have passed through all of the samples.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:32.50,0:11:34.54,Default,,0,0,0,,And because there’s a bandlimit in place,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:34.54,0:11:39.22,Default,,0,0,0,,Nyquist-Shannon proves that the output signal is the exact same one as the input.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:39.22,0:11:43.02,Default,,0,0,0,,To provide some evidence to back this claim up, take a look at this CD player.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:43.02,0:11:45.68,Default,,0,0,0,,This is a Sony CD changer from 1993.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:45.68,0:11:49.72,Default,,0,0,0,,It has a relatively rudimentary DAC in part because it’s a cheaper machine
Dialogue: 0,0:11:49.72,0:11:52.22,Default,,0,0,0,,and in part because it’s older.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:52.22,0:11:56.58,Default,,0,0,0,,Let’s hook an oscilloscope up to it and take a look at the output coming from its RCA jacks,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:56.58,0:11:59.01,Default,,0,0,0,,This is just some music it’s playing right now.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:59.01,0:12:02.48,Default,,0,0,0,,Notice that there’s nothing in here that looks remotely stair-steppy.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:02.48,0:12:08.01,Default,,0,0,0,,But let’s take it even further, I’ve created a CD with various tones generated in Audacity.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:08.01,0:12:10.73,Default,,0,0,0,,Let’s start with a 1 kilohertz square wave.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:10.73,0:12:13.49,Default,,0,0,0,,Even though in Audacity the samples look like this:
Dialogue: 0,0:12:13.49,0:12:16.78,Default,,0,0,0,,straight up, then hold, with a completely straight line between peaks,
Dialogue: 0,0:12:16.78,0:12:19.79,Default,,0,0,0,,the output from the CD player is that wiggly wavy thing.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:20.39,0:12:24.29,Default,,0,0,0,,That happens because those wiggly wavies are the only way to make this square wave
Dialogue: 0,0:12:24.29,0:12:29.56,Default,,0,0,0,,with a 20 kilohertz bandlimit, and the wiggly bits are passing through each of those samples,
Dialogue: 0,0:12:29.56,0:12:33.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Now let’s switch to some sine waves. This is again 1 kilohertz.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:33.00,0:12:36.02,Default,,0,0,0,,This looks perfectly smooth, no stair-steps to be seen.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:36.02,0:12:39.13,Default,,0,0,0,,To be fair, though, even in Audacity it looks pretty good.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:39.13,0:12:44.32,Default,,0,0,0,,Let’s move up to a 10 kilohertz sine wave. Now in Audacity it looks really gnarly,
Dialogue: 0,0:12:44.32,0:12:47.80,Default,,0,0,0,,with the connections between the samples making a barely intelligible wave.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:48.11,0:12:50.25,Default,,0,0,0,,There aren’t even 5 samples per cycle,
Dialogue: 0,0:12:50.25,0:12:54.07,Default,,0,0,0,,so how can the smooth detail of the sine wave possibly be reproduced?
Dialogue: 0,0:12:54.07,0:12:58.35,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, take a look! There’s a perfectly smooth sine wave for you, right there.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:58.35,0:13:02.34,Default,,0,0,0,,This is why some of you cringed when I drew straight lines between the samples.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:02.34,0:13:06.00,Default,,0,0,0,,That’s only sort of what happens, and even then it’s not that accurate.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:06.00,0:13:09.26,Default,,0,0,0,,But it does serve as a sort of blend between the two realities.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:09.26,0:13:13.00,Default,,0,0,0,,There is a stair-step pattern in the intermediate between the resistor ladder
Dialogue: 0,0:13:13.00,0:13:18.13,Default,,0,0,0,,and the low pass filter. So the DAC does connect the dots, but like this.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:18.13,0:13:21.99,Default,,0,0,0,,Then the LPF smooths out the connections between the dots,
Dialogue: 0,0:13:21.99,0:13:25.85,Default,,0,0,0,,but that only happens as a side-effect of the fact that it’s creating a bandlimit.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:25.85,0:13:30.00,Default,,0,0,0,,So the high frequency components, that’s the vertical parts here, get tossed out.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:30.00,0:13:35.00,Default,,0,0,0,,What you’re left with is the only possible waveform that can both hit all the samples,
Dialogue: 0,0:13:35.00,0:13:39.20,Default,,0,0,0,,and which does not contain requency components above Nyquist. {\s1}Simple, right?{\s}
Dialogue: 0,0:13:39.20,0:13:41.99,Default,,0,0,0,,Ah! We haven’t even really talked about the CD itself yet!
Dialogue: 0,0:13:41.99,0:13:44.68,Default,,0,0,0,,And this is pushing into the 14 or 15 minute mark already,
Dialogue: 0,0:13:44.68,0:13:47.02,Default,,0,0,0,,if my gauge of time per written page is at all correct.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:47.70,0:13:51.18,Default,,0,0,0,,OK, I guess we’re going to push the technology of the CD into another video.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:51.18,0:13:54.39,Default,,0,0,0,,But that’s OK, since we covered what makes sound out of numbers.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:54.39,0:13:59.44,Default,,0,0,0,,And hopefully we’ve destroyed the myth that digital audio cannot produce smooth waveforms.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:59.44,0:14:00.30,Default,,0,0,0,,It does,
Dialogue: 0,0:14:00.30,0:14:04.54,Default,,0,0,0,,Much of the information from this video (and indeed some selected clips) came from
Dialogue: 0,0:14:04.54,0:14:09.35,Default,,0,0,0,,a lovely video by Monty at xiph,org. I’ve linked to a great article of his down below,
Dialogue: 0,0:14:09.35,0:14:12.00,Default,,0,0,0,,and a card will pop up now heading to his video.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:12.40,0:14:16.58,Default,,0,0,0,,Many, many people brought this to my attention on Twitter and elsewhere, so thank you.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:17.02,0:14:20.75,Default,,0,0,0,,He’s got some much better demonstrations than I do that cover this topic.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:20.75,0:14:24.77,Default,,0,0,0,,He also explains why the bit depth affects noise, and not clarity,
Dialogue: 0,0:14:24.77,0:14:29.00,Default,,0,0,0,,what dithering is and how it reduces quantization noise, and much more.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:29.00,0:14:32.01,Default,,0,0,0,,But I will give you one last tid-bit before I sign off.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:32.01,0:14:34.56,Default,,0,0,0,,You may have noticed that in the video we’ve been discussing
Dialogue: 0,0:14:34.56,0:14:38.39,Default,,0,0,0,,a theoretical sampling rate of 40 kHz, as this Nyquist sampling rate
Dialogue: 0,0:14:38.39,0:14:41.60,Default,,0,0,0,,could perfectly capture all of what human hearing can pick up.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:41.60,0:14:46.01,Default,,0,0,0,,But the CD standard’s sampling rate is 44.1 kilohertz.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:46.01,0:14:49.33,Default,,0,0,0,,Why the extra 4.1? That seems awfully specific.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:49.33,0:14:52.99,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, that’s due to the fact that low-pass filters aren’t perfect.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:52.99,0:14:55.91,Default,,0,0,0,,They can’t just cut off frequencies above a point,
Dialogue: 0,0:14:55.91,0:14:59.74,Default,,0,0,0,,they instead have a transition window where the frequencies degrade to zero,
Dialogue: 0,0:14:59.74,0:15:04.00,Default,,0,0,0,,The 44,1 kilohertz sampling rate is to accommodate for that window.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:04.00,0:15:07.51,Default,,0,0,0,,Without a hard-cut on the low-pass filter, aliasing could occur
Dialogue: 0,0:15:07.51,0:15:12.17,Default,,0,0,0,,because the samples might define a waveform of a higher frequency than Nyquist.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:12.17,0:15:14.97,Default,,0,0,0,,This is a precisely why we need an LPF.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:14.97,0:15:18.26,Default,,0,0,0,,Both of these waveforms satisfy all the samples,
Dialogue: 0,0:15:18.26,0:15:22.35,Default,,0,0,0,,so to prevent one of them from coming through, we need to decide a limit in frequency.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:22.35,0:15:26.55,Default,,0,0,0,,If the red waveform is above the Nyquist limit, then it won’t get reproduced.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:26.55,0:15:31.45,Default,,0,0,0,,But if the low-pass filter could let slip some signals above our decided sample rate,
Dialogue: 0,0:15:31.45,0:15:33.59,Default,,0,0,0,,scenarios like this might occur.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:33.59,0:15:37.49,Default,,0,0,0,,Therefore, the sample rate was chosen to be 44,1 kilohertz,
Dialogue: 0,0:15:37.49,0:15:42.07,Default,,0,0,0,,that way it exceeds the transition window for our desired 20 kilohertz cutoff.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:42.07,0:15:45.48,Default,,0,0,0,,And by sampling a bit beyond the audible range, we don’t have to worry about
Dialogue: 0,0:15:45.48,0:15:49.09,Default,,0,0,0,,spurious aliasing artifacts from samples in the transition band.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:49.09,0:15:52.46,Default,,0,0,0,,But the more interesting thing about the 44,1 kilohertz rate
Dialogue: 0,0:15:52.46,0:15:57.36,Default,,0,0,0,,is that it was also chosen for easy digital sound storage before a CD gets pressed.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:57.36,0:16:00.28,Default,,0,0,0,,This was the perfect sampling rate for storing sound
Dialogue: 0,0:16:00.28,0:16:04.58,Default,,0,0,0,,on both an NTSC and a PAL U-Matic videocassette recorder.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:04.58,0:16:08.47,Default,,0,0,0,,The commercial VCR format from Sony was among the earliest ways to
Dialogue: 0,0:16:08.47,0:16:13.02,Default,,0,0,0,,store a digital audio stream, using the video signal sort of like a giant QR code.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:13.83,0:16:15.78,Default,,0,0,0,,It’s not literally being read in that sense,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:15.78,0:16:19.56,Default,,0,0,0,,but the data is stored on the tape as a field of black and white bars in each line,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:19.56,0:16:22.90,Default,,0,0,0,,so if watching the output on-screen it would look like a flashing screen of
Dialogue: 0,0:16:22.90,0:16:29.69,Default,,0,0,0,,QR codes whizzing by 60 times per second, 44,1 kHz would, on both NTSC and PAL signals,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:29.69,0:16:32.17,Default,,0,0,0,,work out to 3 samples per video line.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:32.17,0:16:37.48,Default,,0,0,0,,So in a strange twist, the world of analog video dicated how digital sound would work.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:37.48,0:16:39.75,English Right,,0,0,0,,Thanks for watching, I hope you enjoyed the video,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:39.75,0:16:41.80,English Right,,0,0,0,,As I end all of my videos apparently,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:41.80,0:16:43.83,English Right,,0,0,0,,if this is your first time coming across the channel
Dialogue: 0,0:16:43.83,0:16:46.52,English Right,,0,0,0,,and you liked what you saw, please consider subscribing.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:46.52,0:16:48.71,English Right,,0,0,0,,Also, and I know this can sound weird,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:48.71,0:16:50.47,English Right,,0,0,0,,but for those that follow my videos,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:50.47,0:16:53.14,English Right,,0,0,0,,you might want to make sure you are actually subscribed
Dialogue: 0,0:16:53.14,0:16:55.65,English Right,,0,0,0,,Often times YouTube just serves you content because
Dialogue: 0,0:16:55.65,0:16:57.16,English Right,,0,0,0,,it knows you like it, and you might think
Dialogue: 0,0:16:57.16,0:16:58.69,English Right,,0,0,0,,you are subscribed when you aren’t.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:58.69,0:17:00.32,English Right,,0,0,0,,Same goes for all channels, really.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:00.32,0:17:03.13,English Right,,0,0,0,,But I’ll be the selfish one today and post this reminder,
Dialogue: 0,0:17:03.13,0:17:04.72,English Right,,0,0,0,,As always, thank you to everyone who
Dialogue: 0,0:17:04.72,0:17:06.45,English Right,,0,0,0,,supports this channel on Patreon,
Dialogue: 0,0:17:06.45,0:17:09.17,English Right,,0,0,0,,especially the fine folks who are scrolling up your screen.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:09.17,0:17:12.01,English Right,,0,0,0,,Supporters on Patreon have turned my weird hobby of
Dialogue: 0,0:17:12.01,0:17:14.36,English Right,,0,0,0,,making videos about technology into a job,
Dialogue: 0,0:17:14.36,0:17:16.20,English Right,,0,0,0,,and you all deserve my thanks.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:16.20,0:17:17.79,English Right,,0,0,0,,If you would like to pledge some support
Dialogue: 0,0:17:17.79,0:17:20.50,English Right,,0,0,0,,and help the channel grow, please check out my Patreon page,
Dialogue: 0,0:17:20.50,0:17:23.30,English Right,,0,0,0,,Thanks for your consideration, and I’ll see you next time!
Dialogue: 0,0:00:00.06,0:00:02.86,Chinese,,0,0,0,,1982年，索尼和飞利浦之间成功的合作成果
Dialogue: 0,0:00:02.86,0:00:05.92,Chinese,,0,0,0,,向喜爱音乐的公众发布了
Dialogue: 0,0:00:05.92,0:00:11.25,Chinese,,0,0,0,,激光唱片(CD)是第一个面向消费者的数码音频介质
Dialogue: 0,0:00:11.25,0:00:16.48,Chinese,,0,0,0,,12厘米的光盘能存储多达74分钟的高质量数码音频
Dialogue: 0,0:00:11.25,0:00:16.48,Comments,,0,0,0,,注：后来有80分钟的音频CD，因为制造商将轨道间的间隙给缩短了\NJ. Hendrix的Electric Ladyland长75分钟 1986初版为双CD 1990再版为单CD
Dialogue: 0,0:00:16.48,0:00:22.64,Chinese,,0,0,0,,而且多方证实，它能免疫液体伤害，有些微划伤也无碍
Dialogue: 0,0:00:22.64,0:00:27.07,Chinese,,0,0,0,,而且理论上，还可以没有磨损地播放无限次
Dialogue: 0,0:00:20.76,0:00:27.07,Comments,,0,0,0,,Homer：你小子小时候把我多少张盘都划上道子了，结果你现在看成宝了。
Dialogue: 0,0:00:27.07,0:00:30.21,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这是因为，不像以往的介质，将声音编码成
Dialogue: 0,0:00:30.21,0:00:35.82,Chinese,,0,0,0,,模拟的声波信号，再将其录在黑胶或磁带上那样
Dialogue: 0,0:00:35.82,0:00:38.78,Chinese,,0,0,0,,录在CD上的声音信息实际上是一系列采样
Dialogue: 0,0:00:38.78,0:00:42.45,Chinese,,0,0,0,,也就是用来重放声音的一系列指令
Dialogue: 0,0:00:42.45,0:00:44.18,Chinese,,0,0,0,,在任何方面，激光唱片都很重要
Dialogue: 0,0:00:44.18,0:00:44.63,Chinese,,0,0,0,,在任何方面，激光唱片都{\fs100}很{\fs75}重要
Dialogue: 0,0:00:44.63,0:00:45.20,Chinese,,0,0,0,,在任何方面，激光唱片都{\fs100}很重{\fs75}要
Dialogue: 0,0:00:45.20,0:00:46.99,Chinese,,0,0,0,,在任何方面，激光唱片都{\fs100}很重要
Dialogue: 0,0:00:46.99,0:00:50.30,Chinese,,0,0,0,,他体现了在消费级的高品质录音
Dialogue: 0,0:00:50.30,0:00:54.52,Chinese,,0,0,0,,以及原始数据存储方面的巨大进步
Dialogue: 0,0:00:54.52,0:00:58.64,Chinese,,0,0,0,,后者在CD推出后的一段时间内都没有在计算机领域中体现
Dialogue: 0,0:00:54.52,0:00:58.64,Comments,,0,0,0,,注：规定CD-ROM标准的黄皮书在1988年出品，规定音频CD标准的红皮书在1980年出品
Dialogue: 0,0:00:58.82,0:01:01.47,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但是它还是解决了数码音频技术的核心问题
Dialogue: 0,0:01:01.47,0:01:05.71,Chinese,,0,0,0,,它提供了很大的存储空间，来存储在当年看来大到离谱的数据
Dialogue: 0,0:01:05.71,0:01:08.81,Chinese,,0,0,0,,在我们开始介绍CD的具体细节前
Dialogue: 0,0:01:08.81,0:01:12.75,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我们花亿些时间来介绍一下数码音频工作的具体原理
Dialogue: 0,0:01:12.75,0:01:15.84,Chinese,,0,0,0,,话说上回，我提到模数转换器是按照特定的采样频率
Dialogue: 0,0:01:15.84,0:01:20.54,Chinese,,0,0,0,,采样瞬时的模拟声音信号
Dialogue: 0,0:01:20.54,0:01:26.80,Chinese,,0,0,0,,然后数模转换器根据采样，重新生成原先的模拟信号
Dialogue: 0,0:01:26.80,0:01:30.25,Chinese,,0,0,0,,然而，很多人认为这种方式不能完全
Dialogue: 0,0:01:30.25,0:01:33.16,Chinese,,0,0,0,,还原原先模拟信号的每一个细节
Dialogue: 0,0:01:33.16,0:01:37.04,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但万恶的数学又一次打了我们的脸，实际上是可以的
Dialogue: 0,0:01:37.04,0:01:40.43,Chinese,,0,0,0,,现在我们来了解一下采样原理
Dialogue: 0,0:01:40.43,0:01:44.49,Chinese,,0,0,0,,该定理由这两个人发现
Dialogue: 0,0:01:44.49,0:01:50.28,Chinese,,0,0,0,,所以说，该定理也被称为......
Dialogue: 0,0:01:50.28,0:01:53.80,Chinese,,0,0,0,,无论如何，奈奎斯特和香农，以及那两个人
Dialogue: 0,0:01:53.80,0:01:58.09,Chinese,,0,0,0,,均注意到了被截频的信号，也就是不包含
Dialogue: 0,0:01:58.09,0:02:03.24,Chinese,,0,0,0,,高于某种频率的信号，只要采样率为原信号最高频率的两倍
Dialogue: 0,0:02:03.24,0:02:07.32,Chinese,,0,0,0,,就可以被完美地描述（编码）并复现
Dialogue: 0,0:02:07.32,0:02:11.64,Chinese,,0,0,0,,听上去很复杂，所以我尽力来解释
Dialogue: 0,0:02:15.28,0:02:31.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\fs65\pos(872,278)}人类听力范围
Dialogue: 0,0:02:11.64,0:02:17.56,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我们的听力本身就是有带宽限制的，尽管自然界中有高于
Dialogue: 0,0:02:17.56,0:02:23.41,Chinese,,0,0,0,,20kHz的信号，但我们是无法听到的。先不管那些声称能
Dialogue: 0,0:02:23.41,0:02:26.99,Chinese,,0,0,0,,听见的人，大多数人随年龄增长而损失对高频声音的听力
Dialogue: 0,0:02:26.99,0:02:31.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\fs65\pos(868,644)}真的过于简化了！
Dialogue: 0,0:02:26.99,0:02:31.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,那时他们肯定不是小朋友啦，所以我们不考虑了
Dialogue: 0,0:02:31.00,0:02:34.86,Chinese,,0,0,0,,地球人都知道，超过20kHz的声音我们就听不到了
Dialogue: 0,0:02:34.86,0:02:41.06,Chinese,,0,0,0,,所以我们仅需捕获低于20kHz的声音就可以了
Dialogue: 0,0:02:41.06,0:02:44.48,Chinese,,0,0,0,,将模拟信号经过低通滤波器处理后
Dialogue: 0,0:02:44.48,0:02:48.01,Chinese,,0,0,0,,高于某个频率的信号就被截断了
Dialogue: 0,0:02:48.01,0:02:51.02,Chinese,,0,0,0,,毕竟录制我们听不到的信号就是浪费
Dialogue: 0,0:02:51.02,0:02:54.56,Chinese,,0,0,0,,所以我们拿个低通滤波器截下信号就好了
Dialogue: 0,0:02:54.56,0:02:57.74,Chinese,,0,0,0,,最终获得的信号，也就是我们能听到的所有信号了
Dialogue: 0,0:02:57.74,0:03:00.67,Chinese,,0,0,0,,当然，更重要的是，信号的带宽被限制了
Dialogue: 0,0:03:00.67,0:03:03.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,从现在开始，我们假设刚才这套十分理想
Dialogue: 0,0:03:03.00,0:03:08.08,Chinese,,0,0,0,,也就是说，所有高于20kHz频率的信号无法通过低通滤波器
Dialogue: 0,0:03:08.08,0:03:11.76,Chinese,,0,0,0,,由采样原理知，当我们的采样率为40kHz时
Dialogue: 0,0:03:11.76,0:03:15.96,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我们可以采集到该截过频信号的详细信息
Dialogue: 0,0:03:15.96,0:03:20.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,听上去很反直觉，不过我来解释一下这是为什么
Dialogue: 0,0:03:20.00,0:03:28.19,Chinese,,0,0,0,,一个带宽受限的信号可以用一堆正弦波的谐波来表示
Dialogue: 0,0:03:28.19,0:03:33.24,Chinese,,0,0,0,,由傅里叶变换（一会就知道有多腻味人的复杂数学知识）可知
Dialogue: 0,0:03:33.24,0:03:37.86,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我们可以用一大堆正弦波的谐波表示任何波形
Dialogue: 0,0:03:37.86,0:03:40.39,Chinese,,0,0,0,,最经典的示例就是方波了
Dialogue: 0,0:03:40.39,0:03:46.98,Chinese,,0,0,0,,理想方波如上，但要重现方波信号的话，需要接近无限的带宽
Dialogue: 0,0:03:46.98,0:03:48.85,Chinese,,0,0,0,,当然，我早猜到你们会说：嘛玩意？
Dialogue: 0,0:03:48.85,0:03:51.37,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这就是快速地变换高低电平的信号啊
Dialogue: 0,0:03:51.74,0:03:55.02,Chinese,,0,0,0,,就像开关灯一样啊。好吧，你没说错
Dialogue: 0,0:03:55.02,0:03:58.23,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但要重现信号的话，单就垂直部分
Dialogue: 0,0:03:58.23,0:04:01.12,Chinese,,0,0,0,,也就是在无限小的时间内快速抬升电平的部分
Dialogue: 0,0:04:01.12,0:04:04.52,Chinese,,0,0,0,,就需要快到不得了的高频率回复
Dialogue: 0,0:04:04.52,0:04:08.47,Chinese,,0,0,0,,你看啊，我们要是能在无限小的时间内将电平由低变高
Dialogue: 0,0:04:08.47,0:04:12.37,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我们也必须能在同样无限小的时间内拉下电平
Dialogue: 0,0:04:12.37,0:04:16.25,Chinese,,0,0,0,,真要是无限小的话，那就是没有时间了
Dialogue: 0,0:04:16.25,0:04:21.39,Chinese,,0,0,0,,相对应的，就得是无限大的带宽，我们可处理不了
Dialogue: 0,0:04:21.39,0:04:27.20,Chinese,,0,0,0,,当信号经过低通滤波器截到20kHz后，结果如右
Dialogue: 0,0:04:27.20,0:04:32.52,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这就是一堆正弦波通过傅立叶变换生成的类似方波的谐波
Dialogue: 0,0:04:32.52,0:04:36.42,Chinese,,0,0,0,,谐波的最高频率为20kHz
Dialogue: 0,0:04:36.42,0:04:38.83,Chinese,,0,0,0,,由于我们在输入信号时限制信号频率了
Dialogue: 0,0:04:38.83,0:04:42.57,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我们仅需只需处理一堆叠在一起的正弦波信号了
Dialogue: 0,0:04:42.57,0:04:46.40,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我们将其他的波形都可视为一系列正弦波的谐波
Dialogue: 0,0:04:46.40,0:04:50.48,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这就解释了采样原理的正确性
Dialogue: 0,0:04:50.48,0:04:54.81,Chinese,,0,0,0,,若采样从最低值到最高值后，又回到最低值
Dialogue: 0,0:04:54.81,0:05:01.77,Chinese,,0,0,0,,能经过着三个采样点的，只能是奈奎斯特频率为20kHz的正弦波
Dialogue: 0,0:04:54.81,0:05:01.77,Comments,,0,0,0,,奈奎斯特频率：为防止信号混叠需要定义最小采样频率，在这理解为之前说的最高频率吧\NSuperBart: 学计算机的学不学这堆玩意啊？
Dialogue: 0,0:05:01.35,0:05:03.38,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\frz345.7\pos(492,394)}超级完美的正弦波(bushi
Dialogue: 0,0:05:01.77,0:05:06.39,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我们不能获得高于20kHz的信号
Dialogue: 0,0:05:06.39,0:05:09.82,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但是每周期内仅需两个采样，就能确定信号的最高频率
Dialogue: 0,0:05:09.82,0:05:16.51,Chinese,,0,0,0,,当你对信号截频的时候，你也就截去了高于此频率的方波谐波信息
Dialogue: 0,0:05:17.05,0:05:21.20,Chinese,,0,0,0,,现在为防止各位在不应有细节的地方无中生有
Dialogue: 0,0:05:21.20,0:05:26.51,Chinese,,0,0,0,,记住，你所听到的信号和低通滤波器输出的信号一样，都截频了
Dialogue: 0,0:05:26.51,0:05:30.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,还有一件事，整个过程是复杂混乱的
Dialogue: 0,0:05:30.38,0:05:34.01,Chinese,,0,0,0,,自然界的万物都会因能量的瞬息变化而突变
Dialogue: 0,0:05:34.01,0:05:37.08,Chinese,,0,0,0,,就算有一个方波突然出现
Dialogue: 0,0:05:37.08,0:05:40.22,Chinese,,0,0,0,,你的耳膜也是在能量的峰谷之间震动
Dialogue: 0,0:05:37.08,0:05:40.22,Comments,,0,0,0,,注：而来回振动真需要时间啊
Dialogue: 0,0:05:40.22,0:05:43.46,Chinese,,0,0,0,,有点像截频信号上的小波纹
Dialogue: 0,0:05:43.46,0:05:45.84,Chinese,,0,0,0,,所以说，我们不要考虑这个了
Dialogue: 0,0:05:45.84,0:05:51.26,Chinese,,0,0,0,,虽然这曾经让我很迷惑，但实际上，声波和大自然就这德行
Dialogue: 0,0:05:51.68,0:05:54.59,Chinese,,0,0,0,,任意信号可用一系列正弦波合成
Dialogue: 0,0:05:54.59,0:05:58.62,Chinese,,0,0,0,,而截频也就是信号上波纹的来源了
Dialogue: 0,0:05:58.62,0:06:01.69,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这样的表示有一个问题
Dialogue: 0,0:06:01.69,0:06:05.13,Chinese,,0,0,0,,也就是由吉布斯现象搞出来的振铃效应
Dialogue: 0,0:06:01.69,0:06:05.13,Comments,,0,0,0,,振铃效应：出现在信号快速转换时，附加在转换边缘上导致失真的信号\N各位可在各种表情包的边缘上看到这种现象，也就是边缘的模糊
Dialogue: 0,0:06:05.13,0:06:07.52,Chinese,,0,0,0,,不过马上要说的东西就要困难许多了
Dialogue: 0,0:06:07.52,0:06:11.13,Chinese,,0,0,0,,你也能想到，这也能在模拟信号系统上出现
Dialogue: 0,0:06:11.13,0:06:14.70,Chinese,,0,0,0,,还是因为自然界的不确定性，在力学方面
Dialogue: 0,0:06:14.70,0:06:21.18,Chinese,,0,0,0,,比如说，唱针和扬声器驱动单元都有质量的，无法立刻震动
Dialogue: 0,0:06:21.18,0:06:25.58,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这样，他们就有自己的谐波频率了
Dialogue: 0,0:06:25.58,0:06:30.99,Chinese,,0,0,0,,显然，在电学领域中，任何电路都有一些谐波的
Dialogue: 0,0:06:30.99,0:06:32.75,Chinese,,0,0,0,,所以，我们不必考虑
Dialogue: 0,0:06:32.75,0:06:36.44,Chinese,,0,0,0,,接下来你将听到的将会颠覆你的认知
Dialogue: 0,0:06:36.44,0:06:38.46,Chinese,,0,0,0,,一会我来演示一下
Dialogue: 0,0:06:38.46,0:06:44.83,Chinese,,0,0,0,,由采样原理知，我们仅需按原信号限制频率的两倍频率采样
Dialogue: 0,0:06:44.83,0:06:48.54,Chinese,,0,0,0,,该带宽受限信号就可从采样中完美复现
Dialogue: 0,0:06:48.54,0:06:52.62,Chinese,,0,0,0,,真的，就靠这些采样就行哦
Dialogue: 0,0:06:52.62,0:06:55.60,Chinese,,0,0,0,,绝对有点奇怪，接着听介绍吧
Dialogue: 0,0:06:55.60,0:07:00.01,Chinese,,0,0,0,,现在模数转换器正在录音，每四万分之一秒
Dialogue: 0,0:07:00.01,0:07:02.99,Chinese,,0,0,0,,它记录下接收信号的瞬时状态
Dialogue: 0,0:07:02.99,0:07:05.68,Chinese,,0,0,0,,再按照我们规定的量度量化之
Dialogue: 0,0:07:05.68,0:07:08.79,Chinese,,0,0,0,,（每秒钟）就能产生四万个离散采样
Dialogue: 0,0:07:08.79,0:07:14.02,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但是呢，信号在经过模数转换器前已经被低通滤波器截频了
Dialogue: 0,0:07:14.02,0:07:17.74,Chinese,,0,0,0,,所以（采样中）不可能有高于20kHz的信息
Dialogue: 0,0:07:17.74,0:07:21.13,Chinese,,0,0,0,,采样定理最惊人的地方在于
Dialogue: 0,0:07:21.13,0:07:26.55,Chinese,,0,0,0,,由原来的截频信号产生的采样{\b1}只能{\b0}还原为原来的信号
Dialogue: 0,0:07:26.55,0:07:32.80,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\b1}只有{\b0}那一个信号才有可能让ADC产生那一系列的采样
Dialogue: 0,0:07:32.80,0:07:43.31,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\pos(944,486)}当然，任意信号都可以产出很多不同组合的采样\N然而，这些采样组合都只能表示这一个信号
Dialogue: 0,0:07:33.41,0:07:36.01,Chinese,,0,0,0,,当然，这些信号都是被截频的
Dialogue: 0,0:07:36.01,0:07:40.65,Chinese,,0,0,0,,要没设置限制频率的话，由于混叠效应，采样就会被恢复成
Dialogue: 0,0:07:40.65,0:07:43.32,Chinese,,0,0,0,,某种奇怪的波形，不过要是按照限制频率恢复的话
Dialogue: 0,0:07:43.32,0:07:47.64,Chinese,,0,0,0,,那一系列的采样就只能恢复成一种波形了
Dialogue: 0,0:07:47.64,0:07:53.26,Chinese,,0,0,0,,对于限频信号来说，在数学上真的只有一个解能够满足这些采样
Dialogue: 0,0:07:53.26,0:07:54.54,Chinese,,0,0,0,,SuperBart:软件工程专业学这些吗？
Dialogue: 0,0:07:54.56,0:07:56.97,Chinese,,0,0,0,,虽然讲起来真复杂，但你仅需知道
Dialogue: 0,0:07:56.97,0:08:01.25,Chinese,,0,0,0,,仅需一系列的采样，而且假定这些采样仅代表一个截频信号
Dialogue: 0,0:08:01.25,0:08:04.28,Chinese,,0,0,0,,他们就只能满足一个波形了
Dialogue: 0,0:08:04.28,0:08:10.75,Chinese,,0,0,0,,所以，这就是数码音频输出的是类似阶梯信号的说法为啥是错的
Dialogue: 0,0:08:10.75,0:08:14.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,然而有点疑惑的是，数模转换器很有可能会这样做
Dialogue: 0,0:08:14.00,0:08:15.88,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但在惊讶之前，先听我一言，这并不意味着
Dialogue: 0,0:08:15.88,0:08:19.68,Chinese,,0,0,0,,任何类似阶梯的信号会从数模转换器或CD播放器中输出
Dialogue: 0,0:08:19.68,0:08:24.72,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这都是和限制输入信号频率相同的低通滤波器的作用
Dialogue: 0,0:08:24.72,0:08:29.26,Chinese,,0,0,0,,很多数模转换器的原理真的很简单，他们使用了电阻网络
Dialogue: 0,0:08:29.26,0:08:33.96,Chinese,,0,0,0,,他们根据每一位离散采样，产生相对应的电压
Dialogue: 0,0:08:33.96,0:08:35.96,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这里我不想深入太多
Dialogue: 0,0:08:35.96,0:08:38.63,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但是这就是简单的数模转换器的工作原理
Dialogue: 0,0:08:39.17,0:08:41.71,Chinese,,0,0,0,,每一位采样都与一个电阻元件相对应
Dialogue: 0,0:08:41.71,0:08:44.90,Chinese,,0,0,0,,要是“1”的话，电阻元件被激活，电压从其中穿过
Dialogue: 0,0:08:44.90,0:08:46.78,Chinese,,0,0,0,,要是“0”的话，电阻元件就不会被激活
Dialogue: 0,0:08:46.78,0:08:51.56,Chinese,,0,0,0,,而电阻网络将会根据一系列采样的组合产生一独特的电压，因此
Dialogue: 0,0:08:51.56,0:08:55.62,Chinese,,0,0,0,,你可以将一大堆数字信息转换成对应的电压还是啥的
Dialogue: 0,0:08:56.25,0:08:59.84,Chinese,,0,0,0,,用于激光唱片的16位数模转换器
Dialogue: 0,0:08:59.84,0:09:01.70,Chinese,,0,0,0,,（用HDCD，SACD啥的hifi党给我找三门峡的水电去）
Dialogue: 0,0:08:59.84,0:09:01.70,Comments,,0,0,0,,注: 各位有96/24资源的观众，看下频谱图，经常高于20kHz的地方就没信号了
Dialogue: 0,0:09:01.70,0:09:05.71,Chinese,,0,0,0,,有16个电阻元件，分别由一位数据流控制
Dialogue: 0,0:09:05.71,0:09:10.22,Chinese,,0,0,0,,他们产生的电压传入中继电阻元件，以产生各种可能的电压
Dialogue: 0,0:09:10.22,0:09:13.53,Chinese,,0,0,0,,当然，更多位数，结果就会更精确
Dialogue: 0,0:09:13.53,0:09:16.84,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这也就是为啥早期的数模转换器十分昂贵了
Dialogue: 0,0:09:16.84,0:09:19.67,Chinese,,0,0,0,,在集成电路上制作该电阻元件的误差最多0.000015%
Dialogue: 0,0:09:19.67,0:09:26.45,Chinese,,0,0,0,,对于当时的科技水平来说，成本是昂贵的
Dialogue: 0,0:09:26.45,0:09:29.25,Chinese,,0,0,0,,无论如何，这些R-2R电阻网络数模转换器
Dialogue: 0,0:09:29.25,0:09:32.56,Chinese,,0,0,0,,在电阻网络输出端会产生类似阶梯的波形信号
Dialogue: 0,0:09:32.99,0:09:34.87,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这被叫做“取样保持”
Dialogue: 0,0:09:34.87,0:09:39.17,Chinese,,0,0,0,,在下一采样到达数模转换器之前，电压会保持上一采样对应电压值
Dialogue: 0,0:09:39.76,0:09:44.34,Chinese,,0,0,0,,而这就是为啥很多人误认为这个信号
Dialogue: 0,0:09:44.34,0:09:47.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,就是从CD播放器输出到放大器的信号的原因了
Dialogue: 0,0:09:47.00,0:09:52.78,Chinese,,0,0,0,,大家都能想到这玩意承载着贝九交响曲的音频信号啊
Dialogue: 0,0:09:47.00,0:09:52.78,Comments,,0,0,0,,注：索尼副总裁大贺典雄建议光盘能容纳74分钟的音乐\N也就是富特文格勒在1951年指挥的贝九交响曲的长度（当时已知最长的版本）
Dialogue: 0,0:09:52.78,0:09:55.90,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但是，有一点你们没注意到，这个类似阶梯的波形
Dialogue: 0,0:09:55.90,0:09:58.74,Chinese,,0,0,0,,得过一遍低通滤波器截频
Dialogue: 0,0:09:59.04,0:10:02.78,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这样数模转换器输出波形的最高频率
Dialogue: 0,0:10:02.78,0:10:05.47,Chinese,,0,0,0,,和输入进模数转换器波形的最高频率一样
Dialogue: 0,0:10:06.07,0:10:11.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,也就是说，从数模转换器输出的波形也被截频到20kHz
Dialogue: 0,0:10:11.00,0:10:15.16,Chinese,,0,0,0,,为啥这很重要呢？因为这个类似阶梯的输出波形自身的
Dialogue: 0,0:10:15.16,0:10:18.43,Chinese,,0,0,0,,最高频率不仅仅是20kHz那么低
Dialogue: 0,0:10:18.84,0:10:23.16,Chinese,,0,0,0,,就跟方波一样，垂直部分的信号需要无限大的带宽才能承载
Dialogue: 0,0:10:23.74,0:10:24.89,Chinese,,0,0,0,,也许Farnsworth博士有这技术吧
Dialogue: 0,0:10:25.30,0:10:28.76,Chinese,,0,0,0,,而更奇怪的是，也是更难明白的是
Dialogue: 0,0:10:28.76,0:10:32.70,Chinese,,0,0,0,,由于从数模转换器输出信号的最高频率和
Dialogue: 0,0:10:32.70,0:10:35.07,Chinese,,0,0,0,,从模数转换器输出信号的最高频率相同，我们又要利用采样原理了
Dialogue: 0,0:10:35.53,0:10:40.23,Chinese,,0,0,0,,而最奇怪的地方在于，从低通滤波器输出的信号
Dialogue: 0,0:10:40.23,0:10:44.10,Chinese,,0,0,0,,只能是原先模数转换器录得的信号
Dialogue: 0,0:10:44.72,0:10:46.52,Chinese,,0,0,0,,再说一遍，只要信号被截频
Dialogue: 0,0:10:46.52,0:10:49.92,Chinese,,0,0,0,,仅需要将采样频率设为原信号最高频率的两倍
Dialogue: 0,0:10:49.92,0:10:53.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我们就可以使用一系列离散采样来表示原信号所有的信息
Dialogue: 0,0:10:53.59,0:10:56.80,Chinese,,0,0,0,,若生成一满足所有采样的波形的话
Dialogue: 0,0:10:56.80,0:11:00.86,Chinese,,0,0,0,,该波形一定是原先被模数转换器捕捉到的波形
Dialogue: 0,0:11:00.97,0:11:04.67,Chinese,,0,0,0,,实际上，从电阻网络输出的类阶梯信号的垂直部分
Dialogue: 0,0:11:04.67,0:11:08.68,Chinese,,0,0,0,,一点都不重要，因为经低通滤波器截频，垂直部分就会消失
Dialogue: 0,0:11:08.68,0:11:13.32,Chinese,,0,0,0,,现在信号只包含低于20kHz的部分了
Dialogue: 0,0:11:13.71,0:11:17.93,Chinese,,0,0,0,,记住，类阶梯信号中的垂直部分在截频后，是不存在的
Dialogue: 0,0:11:17.93,0:11:19.16,Chinese,,0,0,0,,他们都会是很平滑的
Dialogue: 0,0:11:19.73,0:11:24.26,Chinese,,0,0,0,,而且数模转换器按照每一位采样，输出的电压是准确的
Dialogue: 0,0:11:24.26,0:11:26.71,Chinese,,0,0,0,,波形一定是满足每一采样的
Dialogue: 0,0:11:26.71,0:11:32.50,Chinese,,0,0,0,,也就是在低通滤波器平滑了波形后，波形一定是满足所有采样的
Dialogue: 0,0:11:32.50,0:11:34.54,Chinese,,0,0,0,,由于之前信号就是被截频的
Dialogue: 0,0:11:34.54,0:11:39.22,Chinese,,0,0,0,,根据采样原理，输出的信号和当时输入的信号绝对是相同的
Dialogue: 0,0:11:39.22,0:11:45.68,Chinese,,0,0,0,,为证明以上推论，我拿来了这个1993年索尼生产的CD换碟机
Dialogue: 0,0:11:45.68,0:11:52.22,Chinese,,0,0,0,,它有一个十分基础的数模转换器，因为这台机器廉价，而且陈旧
Dialogue: 0,0:11:52.22,0:11:56.58,Chinese,,0,0,0,,现在我们把RCA输出的信号接到示波器上看看吧
Dialogue: 0,0:11:56.58,0:11:59.01,Chinese,,0,0,0,,目前正在播放一些音乐
Dialogue: 0,0:11:59.01,0:12:02.48,Chinese,,0,0,0,,我们注意到信号上没有任何垂直的部分
Dialogue: 0,0:12:02.48,0:12:08.01,Chinese,,0,0,0,,为了继续探索，我合成了一些波形，并将其刻在CD上
Dialogue: 0,0:12:08.01,0:12:10.73,Chinese,,0,0,0,,现在是1kHz方波
Dialogue: 0,0:12:10.73,0:12:13.49,Chinese,,0,0,0,,就算在Audacity上，也长这样
Dialogue: 0,0:12:13.49,0:12:16.78,Chinese,,0,0,0,,电压直接提升，然后维持这样，最值之间就是一条直线
Dialogue: 0,0:12:16.78,0:12:19.79,Chinese,,0,0,0,,然而CD播放器的输出却有波纹
Dialogue: 0,0:12:20.39,0:12:24.29,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这是因为在20kHz的限制频率下，方波只能长这样
Dialogue: 0,0:12:24.29,0:12:29.56,Chinese,,0,0,0,,而该波纹信号正好能满足每一个采样
Dialogue: 0,0:12:29.56,0:12:33.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,现在，我们使用一些正弦波，先是1kHz的
Dialogue: 0,0:12:33.00,0:12:36.02,Chinese,,0,0,0,,看上去十分平滑，没有垂直部分
Dialogue: 0,0:12:36.02,0:12:39.13,Chinese,,0,0,0,,说真的，在Audacity下看也很完美
Dialogue: 0,0:12:39.13,0:12:44.32,Chinese,,0,0,0,,现在我们用10kHz的正弦波，这会在Audacity下就很难看了
Dialogue: 0,0:12:44.32,0:12:47.80,Chinese,,0,0,0,,直接在各采样之间连线，很难让人觉得这玩意是个正弦波
Dialogue: 0,0:12:48.11,0:12:50.25,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这玩意甚至都不是每循环5个采样
Dialogue: 0,0:12:50.25,0:12:54.07,Chinese,,0,0,0,,那么，平滑的正弦波是怎么由此产生的呢？
Dialogue: 0,0:12:54.07,0:12:58.35,Chinese,,0,0,0,,现在来看看，这里居然生成了如此平滑的正弦波诶
Dialogue: 0,0:12:58.35,0:13:02.34,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这就是为什么有些人在我直接在采样连线时，故意说我错了
Dialogue: 0,0:13:02.34,0:13:06.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,大略上是这样，可连这都不算很准确的示范
Dialogue: 0,0:13:06.00,0:13:09.26,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但这毕竟是将模拟和数字给联系起来了啊
Dialogue: 0,0:13:09.26,0:13:13.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,确实，在电阻网格和低通滤波器之间确实有类阶梯波形
Dialogue: 0,0:13:13.00,0:13:18.13,Chinese,,0,0,0,,所以数模转换器连接采样的方式是这样的
Dialogue: 0,0:13:18.13,0:13:21.99,Chinese,,0,0,0,,然后低通滤波器将该波形平滑化
Dialogue: 0,0:13:21.99,0:13:25.85,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但信号的平滑只是其将波形截频的一个副作用罢了
Dialogue: 0,0:13:25.85,0:13:30.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,所以高频波形部分，也就是这里的垂直部分，全部消失了
Dialogue: 0,0:13:30.00,0:13:35.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,所产生的波形也只能是能满足所有采样的波形了
Dialogue: 0,0:13:35.00,0:13:39.20,Chinese,,0,0,0,,也不包括高于奈奎斯特频率的信号了。真是好理解啊:-P
Dialogue: 0,0:13:39.20,0:13:41.99,Chinese,,0,0,0,,完了，我还没说到激光唱片本身呢:-P
Dialogue: 0,0:13:41.99,0:13:47.02,Chinese,,0,0,0,,刚讲的东西，如果我在台本注释中没写错的话，已经14-15分钟了
Dialogue: 0,0:13:47.14,0:13:48.51,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\pos(1404,324)}真.时间管理大师
Dialogue: 0,0:13:47.70,0:13:51.18,Chinese,,0,0,0,,好吧，也许下期视频我们再说CD科技的视频吧
Dialogue: 0,0:13:51.18,0:13:54.39,Chinese,,0,0,0,,不过也还好，我们已经说过数码音频了
Dialogue: 0,0:13:51.18,0:13:54.39,Comments,,0,0,0,,注：还没看上期视频的，快点去补课去！
Dialogue: 0,0:13:54.39,0:13:59.44,Chinese,,0,0,0,,希望本期视频也能让大家知道，数码音频是能产生光滑波形的
Dialogue: 0,0:13:59.44,0:14:00.30,Chinese,,0,0,0,,就是可以（坚信）
Dialogue: 0,0:14:00.30,0:14:04.54,Chinese,,0,0,0,,本视频中提到的许多东西（以及一些片段）
Dialogue: 0,0:14:04.54,0:14:09.35,Chinese,,0,0,0,,是参考了xiph的Monty工程师的视频，文章链接附下
Dialogue: 0,0:14:00.30,0:14:09.35,Comments,,0,0,0,,注：xiph基金会就是开发FLAC和ogg编码器的组织
Dialogue: 0,0:14:09.35,0:14:12.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,文章中附带了一个视频
Dialogue: 0,0:14:09.35,0:14:12.00,Comments,,0,0,0,,SuperBart：该视频已经被搬运到Bilibili了，故只有视频链接附下
Dialogue: 0,0:14:12.40,0:14:16.58,Chinese,,0,0,0,,很多人向我推荐了这个视频，十分感谢
Dialogue: 0,0:14:17.02,0:14:20.75,Chinese,,0,0,0,,在我准备这个话题时，他提供了很多更好的示例
Dialogue: 0,0:14:20.75,0:14:24.77,Chinese,,0,0,0,,他还解释了位深对噪音的影响，并含糊地指出
Dialogue: 0,0:14:24.77,0:14:29.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,什么是抖动，它是如何减少量化噪声的，还有更多
Dialogue: 0,0:14:29.00,0:14:32.01,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但在视频结束前，我要再说一件事
Dialogue: 0,0:14:32.01,0:14:34.56,Chinese,,0,0,0,,你也许注意到，我在视频中讨论的是
Dialogue: 0,0:14:34.56,0:14:38.39,Chinese,,0,0,0,,理论奈奎斯特采样率，也就是40kHz
Dialogue: 0,0:14:38.39,0:14:41.60,Chinese,,0,0,0,,该频率正好把我们听力范围内的音频信息都采集了下来
Dialogue: 0,0:14:41.60,0:14:46.01,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但激光唱片的采样率为44.1kHz
Dialogue: 0,0:14:46.01,0:14:49.33,Chinese,,0,0,0,,为啥非得多4.1kHz呢，显得过于做作
Dialogue: 0,0:14:49.33,0:14:52.99,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这是因为低通滤波器不是完美的
Dialogue: 0,0:14:52.99,0:14:55.91,Chinese,,0,0,0,,它不能直接把高于限制频率的信息直接删掉
Dialogue: 0,0:14:55.91,0:15:14.19,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\pos(874,250)}低通滤波器
Dialogue: 0,0:14:55.91,0:15:14.19,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\pos(1444,210)}目标限制频率
Dialogue: 0,0:14:55.91,0:14:59.74,Chinese,,0,0,0,,而是设置了一个过渡区间，将高于限制频率以上的信息降至零
Dialogue: 0,0:14:58.64,0:15:08.62,Chinese,,0,0,0,,{\frz26.52\pos(1758,500)}过渡区间
Dialogue: 0,0:14:59.74,0:15:04.00,Chinese,,0,0,0,,44.1kHz的采样率就是为了适应这个过渡区间
Dialogue: 0,0:15:04.00,0:15:07.51,Chinese,,0,0,0,,如果低通滤波器不是一刀去信号的话，混叠现象就会发生
Dialogue: 0,0:15:07.51,0:15:12.17,Chinese,,0,0,0,,因为采样也许会无中生出个高于奈奎斯特频率的波形
Dialogue: 0,0:15:12.17,0:15:14.97,Chinese,,0,0,0,,而混叠现象就是我们需要低通滤波器的原因了
Dialogue: 0,0:15:14.97,0:15:18.26,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这两个正弦波全部满足所有的采样点
Dialogue: 0,0:15:18.26,0:15:22.35,Chinese,,0,0,0,,为防止其中一个输出，我们需要限制频率
Dialogue: 0,0:15:22.35,0:15:26.55,Chinese,,0,0,0,,若红色波形高于奈奎斯特频率的话，该波形就不会被生成
Dialogue: 0,0:15:26.55,0:15:31.45,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但如果低通滤波器不小心放过了一些高于限制频率的信号的话
Dialogue: 0,0:15:31.45,0:15:33.59,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这种情况就会发生
Dialogue: 0,0:15:33.59,0:15:37.49,Chinese,,0,0,0,,所以，将采样率限制为44.1kHz的话
Dialogue: 0,0:15:37.49,0:15:42.07,Chinese,,0,0,0,,就会包括超过20kHz过渡区间内的信号了
Dialogue: 0,0:15:42.07,0:15:45.48,Chinese,,0,0,0,,采样率只需稍微超过人耳的听力范围
Dialogue: 0,0:15:45.48,0:15:49.09,Chinese,,0,0,0,,就不必担心过渡带上的信号导致的混叠效应了
Dialogue: 0,0:15:49.09,0:15:52.46,Comments,,0,0,0,,SuperBart: 没完了是吗:-P
Dialogue: 0,0:15:49.09,0:15:52.46,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但对于44.1kHz，更有意思的是
Dialogue: 0,0:15:52.46,0:15:57.36,Chinese,,0,0,0,,这是在激光唱片上市前就被确定的数码音频采样率
Dialogue: 0,0:15:57.36,0:16:00.28,Chinese,,0,0,0,,对于NTSC制式和PAL制式的录音带来说
Dialogue: 0,0:16:00.28,0:16:04.58,Chinese,,0,0,0,,用这个采样率存储光盘是再好不过了
Dialogue: 0,0:16:04.58,0:16:08.47,Chinese,,0,0,0,,索尼生产的商用VCR是最早用来存储数码音频的格式之一
Dialogue: 0,0:16:08.47,0:16:13.02,Chinese,,0,0,0,,使用视频信号存储，有点像很大的二维码
Dialogue: 0,0:16:13.83,0:16:15.78,Chinese,,0,0,0,,当然，直接放磁带你也看不懂
Dialogue: 0,0:16:15.78,0:16:19.56,Chinese,,0,0,0,,但是存储在磁带上的数据就是一帧帧黑白条带
Dialogue: 0,0:16:19.56,0:16:22.90,Chinese,,0,0,0,,所以，要是将磁带直接播放的话，视频输出就像是一张张
Dialogue: 0,0:16:22.90,0:16:29.69,Chinese,,0,0,0,,二维码在以60帧每秒的刷新率闪烁，根据NTSC和PAL信号刷新率
Dialogue: 0,0:16:29.69,0:16:32.17,Chinese,,0,0,0,,就是44.1kHz，也就是每条扫描线包含三个采样
Dialogue: 0,0:16:32.17,0:16:37.48,Chinese,,0,0,0,,有点奇怪吧，模拟视频竟和数字音频有着不解之缘
Dialogue: 0,0:16:37.48,0:16:39.75,Chinese Right,,0,0,0,,感谢收看，希望大家喜欢！
Dialogue: 0,0:16:39.75,0:16:41.80,Chinese Right,,0,0,0,,在每期视频的最后
Dialogue: 0,0:16:41.80,0:16:43.83,Chinese Right,,0,0,0,,若你是头一回看到他的频道
Dialogue: 0,0:16:43.83,0:16:46.52,Chinese Right,,0,0,0,,而且你喜欢的话，考虑去油管关注一下
Dialogue: 0,0:16:46.52,0:16:48.71,Chinese Right,,0,0,0,,还有，虽然这听上去很奇怪
Dialogue: 0,0:16:48.71,0:16:50.47,Chinese Right,,0,0,0,,但对于关注我的人们
Dialogue: 0,0:16:50.47,0:16:53.14,Chinese Right,,0,0,0,,你也许应该检查一下你是否真订阅了
Dialogue: 0,0:16:53.14,0:16:55.65,Chinese Right,,0,0,0,,有时油管只是给你推荐我的视频
Dialogue: 0,0:16:55.65,0:16:57.16,Chinese Right,,0,0,0,,因为你喜欢看，然后你就认为
Dialogue: 0,0:16:57.16,0:16:58.69,Chinese Right,,0,0,0,,你订阅了，然而你并没有
Dialogue: 0,0:16:58.69,0:17:00.32,Chinese Right,,0,0,0,,对于其他频道同理
Dialogue: 0,0:17:00.32,0:17:03.13,Chinese Right,,0,0,0,,但今天我自私一下，给大家提醒一下
Dialogue: 0,0:17:03.13,0:17:06.45,Chinese Right,,0,0,0,,当然，感谢那些在Patreon上支持我的人
Dialogue: 0,0:17:06.45,0:17:09.17,Chinese Right,,0,0,0,,尤其是左侧滚动字幕中的人
Dialogue: 0,0:17:09.17,0:17:12.01,Chinese Right,,0,0,0,,支持者们的赞助让我把做古怪科技
Dialogue: 0,0:17:12.01,0:17:14.36,Chinese Right,,0,0,0,,视频的爱好变成了一份工作
Dialogue: 0,0:17:14.36,0:17:16.20,Chinese Right,,0,0,0,,十分感谢你们
Dialogue: 0,0:17:16.20,0:17:17.79,Chinese Right,,0,0,0,,如果你想提供一些支持并帮助这个频道
Dialogue: 0,0:17:17.79,0:17:20.50,Chinese Right,,0,0,0,,发展的话，可以去原作者的Patreon页面
Dialogue: 0,0:17:20.50,0:17:23.30,Chinese Right,,0,0,0,,感谢您的支持，下期视频再见！
